# Senior Designer Mode — UI design rules

Always follow these rules when designing or implementing UI in this project.

## Hierarchy and spacing
- **Clear visual hierarchy**: Use distinct type scale (e.g. text-3xl for hero, text-lg for section titles, text-sm for meta). One clear primary headline per view.
- **Consistent spacing**: Use a spacing scale (4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64). Prefer Tailwind spacing (e.g. space-y-6, gap-4, p-6). Avoid one-off values.
- **Breathing room**: Don't crowd content. Use max-width containers (e.g. max-w-4xl) for reading; allow generous padding on small screens.

## Color and contrast
- **Accessible contrast**: Text on background must meet WCAG AA (4.5:1 for body, 3:1 for large text). Use semantic colors (e.g. success green, warning amber) sparingly and consistently.
- **Limited palette**: Prefer a small set of neutrals plus one primary (e.g. slate/gray + blue or emerald). Avoid many competing accent colors.
- **Backgrounds**: Prefer subtle background steps (e.g. bg-background, bg-muted) over heavy borders to separate sections.

## Components (shadcn / Tailwind UI style)
- **Use shadcn/ui components** where they exist: Button, Card, Badge, etc. Use them as designed; don't reinvent.
- **Cards**: Clear border or subtle shadow, rounded corners (rounded-lg), padding inside. Use CardHeader, CardContent, CardFooter for structure.
- **Buttons**: Primary for main action, secondary/outline for secondary. Consistent size (default, sm) and disabled state.
- **Badges**: For status, counts, or labels. Keep text short and legible.

## Typography
- **Font stack**: Prefer system UI or a single custom font (e.g. Inter, Geist). Use font-medium or font-semibold for emphasis, not only color.
- **Line length**: Cap body text around 65–75 characters for readability.
- **Lists and labels**: Use consistent list spacing and label style (e.g. text-sm text-muted-foreground for secondary labels).

## Motion and feedback
- **Subtle motion**: Prefer short, subtle transitions (e.g. transition-colors, hover scale) over heavy animation. Respect prefers-reduced-motion.
- **Loading and empty states**: Always show loading (skeleton or spinner) and empty state (short message + optional CTA). Never leave a blank area without explanation.

## Accessibility
- **Semantic HTML**: Use header, main, section, nav, button, a. Use heading levels in order (h1 → h2 → h3).
- **Focus and keyboard**: Visible focus ring on interactive elements; ensure full keyboard navigation.
- **ARIA when needed**: aria-label, aria-expanded, aria-live for dynamic content. Don't rely on color alone for meaning.

## Responsiveness
- **Mobile-first**: Base layout for small screens; add breakpoints (sm, md, lg) for larger. Test at 320px, 768px, 1024px.
- **Touch targets**: Buttons and links at least 44×44px on touch devices.
- **No horizontal scroll**: Contain content; use overflow-x-auto only for intentional scroll areas (e.g. tables).

## Refinement (avoid template or childish look)
- **Depth**: Use subtle shadow (e.g. shadow-sm) on cards and nav; one very subtle background gradient is enough.
- **Nav**: Real top bar with logo left, optional nav links, primary CTA right.
- **Hero**: One headline; one pill/badge (e.g. Autonomous · Secure · Read-only); one primary CTA.
- **Cards**: Soft shadow + optional small tags (source, category). Use CardHeader/CardContent.
- **Font**: Distinctive sans (e.g. DM Sans, Geist). **Icons**: Consistent set (e.g. Lucide), not mixed SVGs.
- **Avoid**: Loud gradients, multiple accent colors, playful illustrations for research/medical.

## Don'ts
- Don't use more than two font families.
- Don't use tiny font sizes (minimum 14px for body).
- Don't leave "Loading…" or blank sections without a clear state.
- Don't use low-contrast gray-on-gray for primary content.
